EMPLOYEE HANDBOOK
Criminal Investigations Division
Department of Justice

Issued to all incoming personnel.
Read carefully and retain for reference.

---

WELCOME

You have been selected to serve the Criminal Investigations Division.

The work conducted here is sensitive,consequential, and demands the highest
standards of integrity and discretion.

This handbook outlines what the Divisionexpects of you and what you can expect
in return.

---

CONDUCT & CONFIDENTIALITY

All personnel are bound by a Non-Disclosure Agreement signed
at onboarding.

Confidentiality obligations extend beyond the duration of your employment.

Do not discuss:
- case details
- personnel assignments
- investigative methods

This applies outside authorized channels:
not with family,
not with former colleagues,
not with anyone.

Violations are treated as
federal offenses.

---

WORKING HOURS

Standard hours are 40 hours per week, Monday through Friday.

Your schedule will be set by your supervising officer.

Remote work is not permitted without written authorization.

---

PROBATIONARY PERIOD

All new hires serve a 90-day probationary period.

Performance is evaluated at:
- 45 days
- 90 days

Failure to meet expectations
at either review may result
in immediate termination.

---

VACATION & LEAVE

Full-time employees are entitled to 15 paid vacation days per year.

Vacation requests must be submitted at least two weeks in advance.

Approval is subject to operational needs.

Sick leave is allocated separately and is not to be used as vacation.

---

EQUIPMENT & RESOURCES

Division-issued equipment includes:
- access credentials
- devices
- physical materials

All remain the property of the Department at all times.

Equipment must be returned upon separation.

Unauthorized use or removal is grounds for termination and prosecution.

---

SEPARATION

Employees wishing to resign must provide a minimum of two weeks written notice
to their supervising officer.

The Division reserves the right to waive the notice period.

Post-employment obligations, including confidentiality,
remain in full effect as outlinedin your signed agreements.

---

This handbook does not constitute a contract of employment and may be
updated at the Division's discretion.

